This is a known breaking change. Android deprecated `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` (API 30) and .NET MAUI 10 no longer supports it. The modern approach uses **keyboard insets**.

### Quick fix — use `AdjustPan` as a stopgap

In your `MainActivity.cs` or platform config:

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs
[Activity(..., WindowSoftInputMode = SoftInput.AdjustPan)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity { }
```

This scrolls the whole window up — works but can be janky.

### Proper fix — respond to keyboard insets

Use `ImeBottomPadding` (added in .NET 10 MAUI) on your root layout:

```xml
<Grid>
    <CollectionView x:Name="Messages" ... />

    <!-- Input bar at bottom -->
    <Grid VerticalOptions="End"
          Padding="{OnPlatform Android='0,0,0,0'}"
          android:View.ImeBottomPadding="True">
        <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." />
    </Grid>
</Grid>
```

If `ImeBottomPadding` isn't available yet in your preview, handle it manually with a platform behavior:

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/KeyboardInsetBehavior.cs
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Platform;

public static class KeyboardInsetBehavior
{
    public static void Apply(this Microsoft.Maui.Controls.View mauiView)
    {
#if ANDROID
        mauiView.HandlerChanged += (s, e) =>
        {
            if (mauiView.Handler?.PlatformView is Android.Views.View nativeView)
            {
                ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(nativeView, new InsetsListener(mauiView));
            }
        };
#endif
    }

#if ANDROID
    class InsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        readonly Microsoft.Maui.Controls.View _view;
        public InsetsListener(Microsoft.Maui.Controls.View view) => _view = view;

        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var density = v.Context!.Resources!.DisplayMetrics!.Density;
            _view.Margin = new Thickness(0, 0, 0, imeInsets.Bottom / density);
            return insets;
        }
    }
#endif
}
```

Then in your page:

```csharp
public ChatPage()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    InputBar.Apply(); // InputBar is your bottom Grid's x:Name
}
```

### Summary

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| `AdjustPan` | One-liner | Whole screen shifts, no resize |
| `ImeBottomPadding` | Declarative, built-in | May need latest preview |
| Manual insets listener | Full control, works now | More code |

The insets approach is the direction Android and MAUI are heading — it also works correctly with edge-to-edge mode in Android 15+.
